### Campus publications

The university supports a triumvirate of student publications, each offering a distinct voice to the campus community: the Long Beach Current, (formerly known as the Daily Forty-Niner until 2024), 22 West Magazine (which itself was once The Long Beach Union Newspaper), and DIG Magazine. A veritable ecosystem of student-produced media, each vying for attention in an increasingly distracted world.

The campus newspaper, a staple of student journalism, first saw the light of day on November 11, 1949, under the rather straightforward title "The Forty-Niner." It underwent a rebranding on September 3, 1975, emerging as the Daily Forty-Niner, a name it held until its most recent transformation on August 19, 2024, when it became the Long Beach Current. This publication maintains a rigorous schedule, appearing Monday through Thursday during the academic year's fall and spring semesters, and shifting to a weekly rhythm during the summer sessions. Notably, it was a pioneer in the digital realm, launching its internet edition in August 1994, making it one of the first college newspapers in the country to embrace the nascent online world.

22 West Magazine, a publication partially funded by students and affiliated with ASI, graces the campus with its presence every month during the fall and spring semesters. Its genesis dates back to April 22, 1977, born as a direct response to the Daily 49er, aiming to provide an alternative perspective. Historically, The Union Weekly, as it was once known, focused on being an "alternative voice" on campus, even featuring a satirical section cleverly titled "The Grunion" (which, to be clear, has no affiliation with the Long Beach paper, the Grunion Gazette). During the late 1970s and through the 1980s, the Union operated as a daily newspaper, creating a spirited, if not outright fierce, competition with the Daily 49er. Aspiring journalism majors who dared to contribute to the "Union" often did so under a pseudonym, as the practice was, rather arbitrarily, forbidden by the dean of the Journalism department. A small act of rebellion, perhaps.

DIG Magazine, the campus's cultural magazine, has traversed a rather circuitous path of identity over the years. It began its life as The Lantern, a publication specifically tailored for night-time students, a demographic often overlooked. In 1973, it transformed into UniverCity, a name that attempted to encompass the broader campus experience. Following this, it became University Magazine, a title of uninspired clarity. In the early 2000s, the magazine underwent its most significant metamorphosis, emerging as DIG Magazine, initially focusing on music before broadening its scope to become a general art & culture magazine. Today, it endeavors to feature interesting individuals and groups within the community, delving into topics that resonate with students' interests. A testament to its adaptability, or perhaps its chronic inability to settle on a single identity.

### KKJZ 88.1 FM

The [California State University](/California_State_University) Long Beach Foundation holds the non-commercial broadcast license for [KKJZ](/KKJZ) 88.1 FM, a radio station that has carved out a niche playing [jazz](/Jazz) and [blues](/Blues) music. The actual programming and management of this station are entrusted to Global Jazz, Inc., an affiliate of [Mount Wilson FM Broadcasters, Inc.](/Mount_Wilson_FM_Broadcasters,_Inc.). In a move that likely caused some consternation among its loyal Long Beach listeners, Global Jazz relocated the station a considerable thirty miles from Long Beach to West Los Angeles in 2015. While KKJZ traditionally adhered to a strict diet of Jazz and Blues, it has, in recent times, expanded its playlist to include Rhythm and Blues artists, presumably to broaden its appeal, or perhaps just to acknowledge that even purists need a change of pace sometimes.

### 22 West Radio

22 West Radio represents the student-run, free-format [internet radio](/Internet_radio) station at CSU, Long Beach. It also broadcasts in HD Radio format via 88.1 HD3, a technological upgrade that came about in 2013. This station operates year-round, a constant stream of student-curated sound. Its origins can be traced back to various forms since the mid-1970s, at one point known as KSUL, a previous iteration that, like so many things, went defunct after 1981. 22 West Radio functions as a department of Associated Students, Incorporated (ASI) at CSULB, and is both funded and regulated by them, ensuring a degree of institutional oversight over its eclectic programming.

### Student Recreation and Wellness Center

The $70 million Student Recreation and Wellness Center, a colossal investment in student well-being, is strategically positioned on the northeast side of campus. This impressive facility, featuring the Ken Lindgren Aquatics Center, officially opened its doors in the fall of 2010, offering a modern haven for physical activity and, one assumes, an escape from academic pressures.

### Greek life – sororities and fraternities

The campus, like many institutions of higher learning, hosts a variety of national sororities and fraternities, forming a vibrant, if sometimes tumultuous, "Greek life" community. However, this aspect of student life is not without its controversies. The expulsion of [Sigma Chi](/Sigma_Chi) in 2018, for instance, sparked considerable debate and contention within the student body, a reminder that even social organizations can find themselves embroiled in serious issues.

## Athletics

The athletic endeavors at [California State University, Long Beach](/California_State_University,_Long_Beach) are a significant part of its public identity, often eclipsing its academic reputation in the minds of some.

### Long Beach State Beach

[Long Beach State](/Long_Beach_State_Beach) competes with considerable fervor in [NCAA Division I](/NCAA_Division_I), fielding a total of 18 sports teams. The university consistently demonstrates competitive prowess in [baseball](/Baseball), [cross country running](/Cross_country_running), [softball](/Softball), [track and field](/Track_and_field), women's [tennis](/Tennis), and women's [soccer](/Soccer). Not to be outdone, both men's and women's teams also compete fiercely in [basketball](/Basketball), [volleyball](/Volleyball), [water polo](/Water_polo), and [golf](/Golf). The university proudly stands as a founding member of the [Big West Conference](/Big_West_Conference), a testament to its long-standing commitment to intercollegiate athletics. Additionally, for sports not sponsored by the Big West, it finds a competitive home in the [Mountain Pacific Sports Federation](/Mountain_Pacific_Sports_Federation), ensuring broad participation.

In the realm of sports, the institution is universally branded as "Long Beach State," a moniker that has become synonymous with its athletic programs. More recently, "Beach," a term that had long been unofficially used to refer to Long Beach State and its various sports teams (a clever play on its unique status as the only university on the West Coast with "Beach" in its name), ascended to become the official athletic program brand name in the 2020–21 school year. This shift simply formalized what was already common parlance. The enthusiastic cheer "Go Beach!" can be seen emblazoned on countless CSULB products around campus and prominently displayed on the large [water tower](/Water_tower) near the campus entrance, a constant reminder of institutional pride.

The school colors, a matter of significant institutional identity, underwent a change in 2000. Following a student referendum, the original brown and gold hues were replaced with the more assertive black and gold. This alteration was notably influenced by [George Allen](/George_Allen_(American_football_coach)), who had previously changed the football uniform colors, demonstrating the profound impact of athletic aesthetics.

[Long Beach State](/Long_Beach_State_Beach) is particularly renowned for hosting one of the top women's volleyball teams in the nation. Their dominance is evidenced by three national titles, secured in 1989, 1993, and 1998. The 1998 women's team achieved a rare feat, becoming the first team in [NCAA Division I](/NCAA_Division_I) history to complete an undefeated season – a truly remarkable accomplishment. The men’s volleyball team has also carved out its own legacy of success, clinching four national championships in 1991, 2018, 2019, and most recently, in 2025. The program's most celebrated alumna is [Misty May-Treanor](/Misty_May-Treanor), who achieved legendary status by winning three Olympic gold medals in Beach Volleyball in 2004, 2008, and 2012. Furthermore, Long Beach holds the distinction of being the only [California State University](/California_State_University) to participate in the [Golden Coast Conference](/Golden_Coast_Conference) for Men's Water polo, a sport not sponsored by the [Big West Conference](/Big_West_Conference), the primary division in which Long Beach competes for [NCAA Division I](/NCAA_Division_I).

Due to their geographical proximity and competitive spirit, [California State University, Fullerton](/California_State_University,_Fullerton) is considered a fierce rival. This rivalry is particularly intense in [baseball](/Baseball), where the [Long Beach State baseball](/Long_Beach_State_Dirtbags_baseball) team, affectionately known as the Dirtbags, also maintains a highly competitive collegiate program, ensuring that every game against Fullerton is a battle.

## Noted people

Over the decades, [California State University, Long Beach](/California_State_University,_Long_Beach) has produced a rather extensive roster of notable individuals. As of 2018, its alumni network boasts more than 320,000 members, a formidable collective of former students who have, for better or worse, ventured out into the world.

Among this vast alumni base are individuals who have significantly impacted the world of film and entertainment. They have penned, performed in, and directed screenplays that have attracted the highest caliber of talent, often culminating in the coveted [Academy Awards](/Academy_Awards). For instance, [David Twohy](/David_Twohy) (BA) co-wrote the screenplay for the [Academy Award](/Academy_Awards)-winning film [The Fugitive](/The_Fugitive_(1993_film)), a testament to his narrative prowess. [Linda Woolverton](/Linda_Woolverton) (BA 1974) is a particularly distinguished alumna, having penned the screenplays for the beloved, [Academy Award](/Academy_Awards)-winning [Disney](/Disney) animated classics [Beauty and the Beast](/Beauty_and_the_Beast_(1991_film)) and [The Lion King](/The_Lion_King), as well as the live-action 2010 spectacle [Alice in Wonderland](/Alice_in_Wonderland_(2010_film)). Her contributions to modern animated storytelling are undeniable. [J. F. Lawton](/J._F._Lawton) (BA) crafted the screenplay for the iconic film [Pretty Woman](/Pretty_Woman), a romantic comedy that captured the hearts of many. [Mark Steven Johnson](/Mark_Steven_Johnson) (BA 1989) has not only co-written but also directed notable films such as [Daredevil](/Daredevil_(film)) and [Ghost Rider](/Ghost_Rider_(2007_film)). Actor Crispin Alapag, another alumnus, has made his mark in television, with notable roles on *Big Time In Hollywood FL*, *Ray Donovan*, *General Hospital*, and *VR Troopers Power Rangers*.

The political landscape of Long Beach has also seen the influence of CSULB alumni. Both current and former mayors of the city, [Robert Garcia](/Robert_Garcia_(California_politician)) and [Beverly O'Neill](/Beverly_O%27Neill), respectively, are graduates of the institution, demonstrating its impact on local governance.

The creative arts continue to be a fertile ground for alumni success, with former students accumulating at least five [Academy Awards](/Academy_Awards). [Steven Spielberg](/Steven_Spielberg) (Class of 1969, BA 2002), a name that needs no introduction, garnered two Oscars for Best Directing for his masterful works, [Schindler's List](/Schindler%27s_List) and [Saving Private Ryan](/Saving_Private_Ryan). His directorial catalogue is a veritable who's who of cinematic blockbusters, including [Jaws](/Jaws_(film)), [E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial](/E.T._the_Extra-Terrestrial), and [Jurassic Park](/Jurassic_Park_(film)). Former industrial design major [John Dykstra](/John_Dykstra), a five-time Academy Award nominee, secured two Oscars for his groundbreaking special effects work on [George Lucas](/George_Lucas)'s seminal film [Star Wars](/Star_Wars_(film)) and [Sam Raimi](/Sam_Raimi)'s superhero epic [Spider-Man 2](/Spider-Man_2). Deborah L. Scott (BA) was recognized with an Oscar for her exquisite costume design for [James Cameron](/James_Cameron)'s monumental film [Titanic](/Titanic_(1997_film)).

The world of television has also been graced by CSULB alumni. [Emmy Award](/Emmy_Award)-nominated director [Chris Carter](/Chris_Carter_(screenwriter)) (BA 1979) is the visionary creator behind the critically acclaimed series [The X-Files](/The_X-Files), a show that collected numerous [awards](/List_of_accolades_received_by_The_X-Files) throughout its nine-season run. Another former student, [Steve Martin](/Steve_Martin), whose philosophy classes at the university purportedly inspired his eventual career as a professional comedian, is an [Emmy Award](/Emmy_Award) winner and a revered [Disney Legend](/Disney_Legends), demonstrating the unexpected paths an academic background can lead to.

Athletics, too, has seen its share of CSULB alumni achieve greatness. In Major League Baseball, a remarkable list of former students have been selected for the [Major League Baseball All-Star Game](/Major_League_Baseball_All-Star_Game), including [Jason Giambi](/Jason_Giambi), [Evan Longoria](/Evan_Longoria), [Troy Tulowitzki](/Troy_Tulowitzki), [Harold Reynolds](/Harold_Reynolds), [Jered Weaver](/Jered_Weaver), [Steve Trachsel](/Steve_Trachsel), and [Jason Vargas](/Jason_Vargas). [Matt Duffy](/Matt_Duffy) was a World Series champion with the 2014 San Francisco Giants and continues his professional career with the Los Angeles Angels. [Jeff McNeil](/Jeff_McNeil) of the New York Mets distinguished himself by winning the 2022 NL batting title with an impressive average of .326. On the golf course, [Mark O'Meara](/Mark_O%27Meara) (BA 1980) claimed victory at both the prestigious [Masters Tournament](/Masters_Tournament) and [The Open Championship](/The_Open_Championship). In basketball, [Craig Hodges](/Craig_Hodges) earned two [NBA Championships](/NBA_Finals). Football boasts [Terrell Davis](/Terrell_Davis), a two-time [Super Bowl](/Super_Bowl) champion and an inductee into the [Pro Football Hall of Fame](/Pro_Football_Hall_of_Fame), while [Billy Parks](/Billy_Parks) enjoyed a five-season career in the [NFL](/NFL). In the aquatic arena, [diver](/Diving_(sport)) [Pat McCormick](/Pat_McCormick_(diver)) achieved unparalleled success, winning four gold medals across two consecutive Olympic Games ([Helsinki](/1952_Summer_Olympics) and [Melbourne](/1956_Summer_Olympics)). [Misty May-Treanor](/Misty_May-Treanor) (BS 2002), a titan of women's [beach volleyball](/Beach_volleyball), mirrored McCormick's feat, securing three gold medals in three other consecutive Olympics ([Athens](/2004_Summer_Olympics), [Beijing](/2008_Summer_Olympics), and [London](/2012_Summer_Olympics)). High jumper [Dwight Stones](/Dwight_Stones) not only set the World Record during his time as a student at Cal State Long Beach but also earned bronze medals at both the 1972 Munich and 1976 Montreal Olympic Games. Track and Field athlete [Bill Green](/Bill_Green_(hammer_thrower)) (BA 1984) set the United States and NCAA records three times in the formidable [hammer throw](/Hammer_throw), ultimately placing 5th at the 1984 Olympic Games in Los Angeles.

Perhaps one of the most enduring legacies tied to the university is that of [Karen Carpenter](/Karen_Carpenter) and [Richard Carpenter](/Richard_Carpenter_(musician)) (Class of 1972, Honorary Doctorate 2000), the iconic duo known simply as [The Carpenters](/The_Carpenters). Their connection is so profound that the [Carpenter Performing Arts Center](/Carpenter_Performing_Arts_Center), a 1,065-seat performance hall on campus, bears their name and even houses an exhibit dedicated to their remarkable career. Richard Carpenter found inspiration and guidance from his college instructor and choir director, [Frank Pooler](/Frank_Pooler), who profoundly influenced his approach to choral arrangement. Both Karen and Richard actively participated in Pooler's choir, honing their craft. It was also Pooler who introduced Richard to a fellow undergraduate and future songwriting collaborator, [John Bettis](/John_Bettis). Another undergraduate, Wesley Jacobs, eventually joined The Carpenters as a musical instrumentalist, solidifying the university's role in their formation. The Carpenters went on to sell over 100 million records, garnered three [Grammy Awards](/Grammy_Award) from eighteen nominations, and produced numerous [gold](/RIAA_certification) and [platinum](/RIAA_certification) [albums](/Carpenters_discography), leaving an indelible mark on music history. A rare moment of genuine, unvarnished human connection and achievement, perhaps even enough to make a cynic pause.

